 much better\nthan we expected. We want to\n-.ii I\ntoll our friends about it. We came\nby .steamer to Washington, arrived j\nHfere \"kitutday mrtrntng. The i\nday was dark and dreary and we i\nremained in doors. Sunday mom\ning we attended the Metropolitan\nMener, al M. E. church, were bon\nored by being seated in the Presi\ndent McKinley pew, and many little,\nattentions shown us, which we ap- 1\nprecioted. The lesson read was One,\nof the Epistles to the Corinthian\u00bb.\nWe are charmed with the beauty\nof the Capitol Cifv, its wide, w it\u00ab\nstreets, its stately homes, beautiful r\nparks but shouid you ask us about Y\nMt. Vernon and the Potomac, we\nwill only say the historic river and j\nthe dear old home was an\ntion to us. I do not- think that in\na1 the land there is a prettier sight\nthan Mt. Vernon. The old home is\non the hillside with the Potomac\nrolling at its feet to the right the\nsheep browsing on the distant Ulis,\nto the left the scene was worthy the\nbrush of some noted landscape\npainter. Yet, with all its beauty it\nseemed to mo that a lonely, pathetic\nair clings 'round nit. Vernon It\nmay be the sacred stillness of the j\nplace perhaps it is in the song of j\nriver, or because the white-sailed\nships are sileat as they puss the sac-\nred grounds.\nWe are a romantio people, and j\nperhaps after all it is because we\nknow thutpalyfor Miss Ann Purnela\nI\n\nSEE THE GOLD BOOT SIGN\n\nHaving made op a nice lot of Hard-Service Boots and\nShoes during the summer, will sell cheaper than any\nother shoemaker can afford. The shoes are all water\nproof, heavy double sole and\nWill Wear With Good Treatment, 12 to 18 Months\nWorth $7.00 and $8.00\u2014go at $5.00 and $5.50. Yes\nSir! They are just as represented. In our repairing\ndepartment we are prompt and can do your work the\nsame day we receive it. Half-soles sewed for the same\nprice you pay for nailed soles. Send your work to\n\nJ. H. Roach's Shoe Shop,\nJ\n507 Foote Street.\nTHE CORINTHIAN $1 A YEAR.\nand the D. A. R's this historic spot\nwould be neglected--desecrated\nground. We saw the old kitchen\nwith its wide old fashioned fire\nplace, und its fire dogs. We saw\nj the colonial cooking utensels and\nthe great brass warming puns that\nthey used to heat the beds with dnr\ning the winter nights. These are\nquite a curiosity. Washington's\ntrunk is there;, and his uniform,\nwith many other priceless relics of\nthat distant time. Souvenirs of\n*be place are sold to help support it.\nAnother scene, a sight, dear to all\nSouth' rners, was the home of Robt.\nLec 1 'engine with what feelings\nthe delegates from Dixie viewed the\nUr\u00ab) it, timiini -,i,\u201e\u201e i? i 17 \u00ee\ngreat v ide portico whore Robt. E.\nj f-*-' 0 u )u, 'k ->nu lorth vilnlo lie i\ni isAdiditig bis HttVf \u2014deciding\ni whether to lean to the North or the j\nSouth, way back in 61 Virginia\nj'bd not call in vain to her chieftUm\nahore donned tl.e gray\n,uk1 honored the name of Lee.\n1 ertr Ihe Lee home is the Hall of\nTame, where they object to a\nSouthern chief tun s name. In Un\n,b is\nfor th Lonfedorato dead. The\nr <lovernnu n f owns and supports the\nY ou oo:, antl '\"'\"\"\"'\"'b' it is\n,,r One of the handsomest, mon\nj u,mint the grounds is the one\n1\nra A r tor\n\nI will let my companion delegate\nfrom Corinth Chapter tell of file\nt-'onvtnUon. I represent Mimisstp\npi on the BMloh Monumental Com\nmittee. I was proud of the appoint\nmeut, but not proud to come before\nthis body of noble women and re\nl* ,irT three dollars collected from;\nj the entire state after a year's work,\nj Mississippi and her gallant, sons\nturned a deaf our to my \"Plea fori\nHhiloli while the representatives\n[from other states report large sums\nj collected to rear a monument to the\nmemory of our dear beys who fell\nion Hhiloh 's bloody field.\nStllea-MeCord\n;T0\nA weddihg of attractive appoint-1\nments took place laRt evening at the\nhome of the bride's mother, 2609\nTwentieth\navenue, 